    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The U.S. Wallows in Hypocrisy on Iran; Pre-election Deal?</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In "The Right Way to Rerun 1980" (editorial, Aug. 7), you are correct in saying our democracy "cannot survive without public accountability." However, I disagree that "exposure is the best safeguard against . . . repetition" of the alleged deal to prevent the release of the American hostages in Iran in 1980.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In "The Right Way to Rerun 1980" (editorial, Aug. 7), you are correct in saying our democracy "cannot survive without public accountability." However, I disagree that "exposure is the best safeguard against . . . repetition" of the alleged deal to prevent the release of the American hostages in Iran in 1980.</p>
        <p>The best safeguard is prosecution of those involved. If anyone in the Reagan-Bush campaign was involved in such a hostage deal, it would surely be a crime and must be punished, even if it means a charge of treason.</p>
        <p>If Mr. Bush or Mr. Reagan knew such a deal was being made, our democracy's true strength rests not merely in exposure, but in the prosecution of these men for their crimes.</p>
        <p>The Congressional investigators must understand the seriousness of these charges, which must be acted upon, if found to be true, to deter future crimes against American democracy. All else is political posturing and a waste of the taxpayer's money. JONATHAN PRINCE Athens, Ohio, Aug. 7, 1991</p>
      </block>
